This is a great find! However, I don't like the approach to set this from command line. For example if maven support is used in a platform application with a custom launcher it will be broken. So what do you think about this variant:

```java
package org.netbeans.modules.maven;

import org.openide.modules.OnStart;

/**
 * Disable the maven global cache. With the cache enabled updates to the pom
 * or the dependencies are not picked up correctly.
 *
 * @see <a href="https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/NETBEANS-4341">NETBEANS-4341</a>
 * @see <a href="https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MNG-6530">MNG-6530</a>
 */
@OnStart
public class MavenCacheDisabler implements Runnable {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        System.setProperty("maven.defaultProjectBuilder.disableGlobalModelCache", "true");
    }
}
```

I'm waiting for my build to finish, but it should work, as the maven property is reevaluated at each run.

Edit: Added missing @OnStart

Ok makes sense, so this would be what you mean:

```java
package org.netbeans.modules.maven;

import org.openide.modules.OnStart;

/**
 * Disable the maven global cache. With the cache enabled updates to the pom
 * or the dependencies are not picked up correctly.
 *
 * @see <a href="https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/NETBEANS-4341">NETBEANS-4341</a>
 * @see <a href="https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/MNG-6530">MNG-6530</a>
 */
@OnStart
public class MavenCacheDisabler implements Runnable {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        if(System.getProperty("maven.defaultProjectBuilder.disableGlobalModelCache") == null) {
            System.setProperty("maven.defaultProjectBuilder.disableGlobalModelCache", "true");
        }
    }
}
```

